artford]] (loan)\n|[[2013\u201314 Football Conference|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"Soccerbase 2013/2014\">{{Soccerbase season|47578|2013|name=Tommy Forecast|access-date=1 April 2016}}</ref>\n|Conference Premier\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||2||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!34!!0!!5!!0!!0!!0!!4!!0!!43!!0\n|}\n\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forecast, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Southampton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Eastbourne Borough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Thurrock F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bromley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Gillingham F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chelmsford City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dartford F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:National League (English football) players]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Forecast"}
{"title_page": "Joseph Okito", "text_new": "{{short description|Congolese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Joseph Okito\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|office      = First Vice-President of the Senate of the Republic of the Congo\n|president   = \n|term_start  = 22 June 1960\n|term_end    = 14 September 1960\n|successor   = [[Isaac Kalonji]]\n|office2     = Senator from [[Kasai Province]]\n|term_start2 = May 1960\n|term_end2   = 17 January 1961\n|birth_date  = 5 February 1910\n|birth_place = Koyapongo, [[Lusambo|Lusambo Territory]], [[Belgian Congo]]\n|death_date  = 17 January 1961\n|death_place = Near [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], [[State of Katanga]]\n|party       = [[Mouvement National Congolais]]\n}}\n'''Joseph Okito''' (5 February 1910 \u2013 17 January 1961) was a Congolese politician and close political ally to [[Patrice Lumumba]] who briefly served as First Vice-President of the [[Senate of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Senate]] of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] (then [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]). He was executed alongside Lumumba in [[State of Katanga|Katanga]] in 1961.\n\n== Biography ==\nJoseph Okito was born on 5 February 1910{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} in the village of Koyapongo, [[Lusambo|Lusambo Territory]], [[Belgian Congo]]. He worked for the colonial administration for many years, serving as the chief of the Batetela sector of the Lusambo Territory. He was cited by the ''[[\u00e9volu\u00e9s]]'' of [[Kananga|Luluabourg]] in a March 1944 memorandum as an example of a dedicated civil servant.{{sfn|Cahiers Africains|2004|p=252}} He was later admitted into the Union des Interets Sociaux Congolais, an elite cultural society for ''\u00e9volu\u00e9s''.{{sfn|Kasongo|1998|p=85}} Okito enjoyed an elevated social status due to his entrepreneurship and significant ownership of property. He was co-opted into the Kasai Provincial Council in 1957, serving until 1959. During the same time he regularly contributed to the monthly ''Communaut\u00e9 de Luluabourg'' in Otetela, Tshiluba, and French.{{sfn|Cahiers Africains|2004|p=252}} The colonial administration selected him as one of two Congolese to be trained to take over the role of commissioner of the [[Sankuru]] district. Okito thought the training would assist him in a future political career. He was sent to Lusambo to shadow the district commissioner and was educated on the principles of administration for one hour each day.{{sfn|Turner|1973|pp=289\u2013290}} In 1959 he founded and became president of the Union rurale du Congo.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} The union later merged into the moderate [[Parti National du Progr\u00e8s]], but Okito was convinced by [[Patrice Lumumba]] to join the nationalist the [[Mouvement National Congolais]] (MNC).{{sfn|Turner|1973|p=257}} The following year he became president of the Sankuru chapter of the party.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}}\n\nIn March 1960 Okito participated in the Akutshu-Anamongo Congress of [[Lodja]], serving as one of the conference's vice presidents.{{sfn|Turner|1973|p=262}} Later he was made a [[Senate of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|senator]] from [[Kasai Province]] of the independent [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]].{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} On 22 June 1960 he was elected First Vice-President of the Senate.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|pp=76\u201377}} In early September Prime Minister Lumumba was fired by President [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]. Lumumba challenged the action and a political impasse ensued.{{sfn|Makombo|2015|p=10}} {{efn|According to Makombo, on 7 September Okito became a member of an \"arbitration commission\" established by Parliament to mediate the dispute.{{sfn|Makombo|2015|p=10}} Hoskyns and Artigue do not list Okito as a member of the commission.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|p=219}}{{sfn|Artigue|1961|p=311}}}} On 14 September [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]] launched a coup that removed Lumumba from power and adjourned Parliament.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=362}}\n\nIn late November Lumumba fled political hostility in the capital to organise [[Free Republic of the Congo|a new government]] in [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]]. He was captured before he could complete his escape and imprisoned at the army camp in [[Thysville]]. Okito was preemptively arrested near [[Kikwit]] and was later transferred to the camp, along with Minister of Youth and Sports [[Maurice Mpolo]].{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=93}} On 17 January 1961, discipline in the base faltered and all three men were flown to [[\u00c9lisabethville]], capital of the secessionist [[State of Katanga]]. Once there, they were brutally tortured at the hands of [[Mo\u00efse Tshombe]] and [[Godefroid Munongo]], Lumumba's chief political rivals and the leaders of the secessionist state.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|pp=126\u2013127}} That night, one by one they were lined up against a tree to be executed via firing squad. Okito was the first to be shot. As he was led to the tree, he said, \"I want my wife and children in L\u00e9opoldville to be taken care of,\" to which someone replied, \"We're in Katanga, not in L\u00e9o!\" Following the execution his body was immediately placed in a nearby grave.{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=120}}\n\nOn 17 January 2011, a [[Thanksgiving after Communion|mass of thanksgiving]] was held in memory of Mpolo and Okito at the Notre-Dame Cathedral in [[Kinshasa]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.radiookapi.net/actualite/2011/01/17/50eme-anniversaire-de-la-mort-de-lumumba-mpolo-et-okito-honores| title = 50\u00e8me anniversaire de l'assassinat de Lumumba: Mpolo et Okito honor\u00e9 | date = 17 January 2011| publisher = [[Radio Okapi]]| access-date = 12 January 2017| language = French}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book| last= Artigue |first= Pierre |title = Qui sont les leaders congolais?|series= Carrefours Africains| publisher = \u00c9ditions Europe-Afrique| volume = 3| date = 1961| ref = harv| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=24c5AQAAIAAJ&dq=|location=Brussels|oclc=469948352}}\n* {{cite book| title = Cahiers Africains| publisher = Centre d'\u00e9tude et de documentation africaines| volume = 75\u201380| date = 2004| location = Brussels| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8u4sAQAAIAAJ&q=| issn = 1021-9994| ref = {{harvid|Cahiers Africains|2004}}}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gondola | first = Ch. Didier| title = The History of Congo | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| series = Greenwood histories of the modern nations| ISSN = 1096-2905| edition = illustrated, annotated| date = 2002| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780313316968| url-access = registration | isbn = 9780313316968|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Heinz| first = G.| last2 = Donnay| first2 = H.| title = Lumumba Patrice: les cinquante derniers jours de sa vie| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| date = 1976| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K_oMAQAAIAAJ&dq=| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Hoskyns| first = Catherine| title = The Congo Since Independence: January 1960 \u2013 December 1961| publisher = Oxford University Press| date = 1965| location = London| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Kasongo| first = Michael| title = History of the Methodist Church in the Central Congo| publisher = University Press of America| date = 1998| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XvTyMBHwmYEC&dq=| isbn = 9780761808824| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Makombo| first = Jean-Marie Mutamba| title = Autopsie du gouvernement au Congo-Kinshasa: Le Coll\u00e8ge des Commissaires g\u00e9n\u00e9raux (1960-1961) contre Patrice Lumumba| publisher = Editions L'Harmattan| date = 2015| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=cDafCgAAQBAJ&dq= | isbn = 9782336392158| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Turner| first = Thomas Edwin| title = A Century of Conflict in Sankuru (Congo-Zaire)| publisher= University of Wisconsin |location = Madison| oclc = 38789852| date = 1973| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=1xZBAAAAIAAJ&q=| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = de Witte| first = Ludo| title = The Assassination of Lumumba| publisher = Verso| edition = illustrated| date = 2002| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bTdlU4yGB6YC&dq=| isbn = 9781859844106| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Young| first = M. Crawford| title = Politics in the Congo: Decolonization and Independence|location= Princeton| publisher = Princeton University Press| date = 1965| ref = harv| oclc= 307971}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Okito, Joseph}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:People from Sankuru]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mouvement National Congolais politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]\n[[Category:People murdered in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Democratic Republic of the Congo politicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo torture victims]]\n[[Category:Executed Democratic Republic of the Congo people]]\n[[Category:People of the Congo Crisis]]\n[[Category:\u00c9volu\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:1961 murders in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Congolese politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Joseph Okito\n|image       =\n|caption     =\n|office      = First Vice-President of the Senate of the Republic of the Congo\n|president   = \n|term_start  = 22 June 1960\n|term_end    = 14 September 1960\n|successor   = [[Isaac Kalonji]]\n|office2     = Senator from [[Kasai Province]]\n|term_start2 = May 1960\n|term_end2   = 17 January 1961\n|birth_date  = 5 February 1910\n|birth_place = Koyapongo, [[Lusambo|Lusambo Territory]], [[Belgian Congo]]\n|death_date  = 17 January 1961\n|death_place = Near [[Lubumbashi|\u