he union later merged into the moderate [[Parti National du Progr\u00e8s]], but Okito was convinced by [[Patrice Lumumba]] to join the nationalist the [[Mouvement National Congolais]] (MNC).{{sfn|Turner|1973|p=257}} The following year he became president of the Sankuru chapter of the party.{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}}\n\nIn March 1960 Okito participated in the Akutshu-Anamongo Congress of [[Lodja]], serving as one of the conference's vice presidents.{{sfn|Turner|1973|p=262}} Later he was made a [[Senate of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|senator]] from [[Kasai Province]] of the independent [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]].{{sfn|Heinz|Donnay|1976|p=10}} On 22 June 1960 he was elected First Vice-President of the Senate.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|pp=76\u201377}} In early September Prime Minister Lumumba was fired by President [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]. Lumumba challenged the action and a political impasse ensued. On 7 September Okito became a member of an \"arbitration commission\" established by Parliament to mediate the dispute.{{sfn|Makombo|2015|p=10}}{{efn|Hoskyns and Artigue do not list Okito as a member of the commission.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|p=219}}{{sfn|Artigue|1961|p=311}}}} On 14 September [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]] launched a coup that removed Lumumba from power and adjourned Parliament.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=362}}\n\nIn late November Lumumba fled political hostility in the capital to organise [[Free Republic of the Congo|a new government]] in [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]]. He was captured before he could complete his escape and imprisoned at the army camp in [[Thysville]]. Okito was preemptively arrested near [[Kikwit]] and was later transferred to the camp, along with Minister of Youth and Sports [[Maurice Mpolo]].{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=93}} On 17 January 1961, discipline in the base faltered and all three men were flown to [[\u00c9lisabethville]], capital of the secessionist [[State of Katanga]]. Once there, they were brutally tortured at the hands of [[Mo\u00efse Tshombe]] and [[Godefroid Munongo]], Lumumba's chief political rivals and the leaders of the secessionist state.{{sfn|Gondola|2002|pp=126\u2013127}} That night, one by one they were lined up against a tree to be executed via firing squad. Okito was the first to be shot. As he was led to the tree, he said, \"I want my wife and children in L\u00e9opoldville to be taken care of,\" to which someone replied, \"We're in Katanga, not in L\u00e9o!\" Following the execution his body was immediately placed in a nearby grave.{{sfn|de Witte|2002|p=120}}\n\nOn 17 January 2011, a [[Thanksgiving after Communion|mass of thanksgiving]] was held in memory of Mpolo and Okito at the Notre-Dame Cathedral in [[Kinshasa]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.radiookapi.net/actualite/2011/01/17/50eme-anniversaire-de-la-mort-de-lumumba-mpolo-et-okito-honores| title = 50\u00e8me anniversaire de l'assassinat de Lumumba: Mpolo et Okito honor\u00e9 | date = 17 January 2011| publisher = [[Radio Okapi]]| access-date = 12 January 2017| language = French}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Citations ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book| last= Artigue |first= Pierre |title = Qui sont les leaders congolais?|series= Carrefours Africains| publisher = \u00c9ditions Europe-Afrique| volume = 3| date = 1961| ref = harv| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=24c5AQAAIAAJ&dq=|location=Brussels|oclc=469948352}}\n* {{cite book| title = Cahiers Africains| publisher = Centre d'\u00e9tude et de documentation africaines| volume = 75\u201380| date = 2004| location = Brussels| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8u4sAQAAIAAJ&q=| issn = 1021-9994| ref = {{harvid|Cahiers Africains|2004}}}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gondola | first = Ch. Didier| title = The History of Congo | publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| series = Greenwood histories of the modern nations| ISSN = 1096-2905| edition = illustrated, a