\u6c11\u9769\u547d\u5fe0\u70c8\u7960\u5927\u6bbf 20120818.jpg|[[National Revolutionary Martyrs' Shrine]], Taipei.\n</gallery>\n\n;Newly built traditional Chinese architecture\n<gallery>\nFile:\u8cf4\u654f\u796d\u7940\u516c\u696d.JPG|[[Taiwan Lai Family Ancestral Hall]], Taichung\nFile:Zhen-Wu Temple in Wuci Township.JPG|[[Wuqi Zhenwu Temple]], Taichung (1849)\nFile:Taichung Le Cheng Matsu Temple.JPG|[[Taichung Le Cheng Matsu Temple]], Taichung (1790)\nFile:Wanhe Temple.jpg|[[Wan He Temple]], Taichung (1684)\nFile:Taichung Folklore Park.JPG|[[Taichung Folklore Park]], Taichung\nFile:\u6b66\u660c\u5bae.JPG|[[Wu Chang Temple]], Nantou County (1903, rebuilt 2010)\nFile:Nankunshen Temple, Jade Emperor Shrine (Taiwan).jpg|[[Nan Kun Shen Dai Tian Temple]], Tainan (1662)\n</gallery>\n\n;Modern Architecture\n<gallery>\nFile:Taipei101.portrait.altonthompson.jpg|[[Taipei 101]], Taipei (2004)\nFile:Taipei_Nan_Shan_Plaza_20171216c.jpg|[[Taipei Nan Shan Plaza]], Taipei (2018)\nFile:Tuntex Sky Tower.JPG|[[85 Sky Tower]], Kaohsiung (1997)\nFile:Chang-Gu_WTC.jpg|[[Chang-Gu World Trade Center]], Kaohsiung (1992)\nFile:THU_Luce_Memorial_Chapel.jpg|[[Luce Memorial Chapel|Tunghai University Luce Memorial Chapel]], Taichung (1963)\nFile:Taichung_Sun_Yat-sen_Hall.JPG|[[Chung Shan Hall]], Taichung\nFile:Taiwan HighSpeedRail HsinChu Station 3.JPG|[[THSR Hsinchu Station|Hsinchu Station]], Hsinchu (2006)\nFile:\u862d\u967d\u535a\u7269\u9928.jpg|[[Lanyang Museum]], Yilan County (2010)\nFile:Taipei-fine-arts-museum.jpg|[[Taipei Fine Arts Museum]], Taipei (1983)\nFile:WorkdGame2009 Stadium completed.jpg|[[National Stadium (Kaohsiung)|National Stadium]], Kaohsiung (2009)\nFile:Taichung City Building.JPG|[[Taichung City Government|Taichung City Government Building]], Taichung\nFile:\u65b0\u5317\u5e02\u653f\u5e9c_New_Taipei_city_hall_-_panoramio.jpg|[[New Taipei City Hall]], New Taipei City (2003)\nFile:\u79d1\u535a\u9928\u690d\u7269\u5712.jpg|[[National Museum of Natural Science]], Taichung (1986)\nFile:TpmlBeitou.JPG|[[Taipei Public Library Beitou Branch|Taipei Public Library]], Taipei (2006)\nFile:\u570b\u8cc7\u5716\u7e3d\u9928.jpg|[[National Library of Public Information]], Taichung\nFile:\u81fa\u4e2d\u570b\u5bb6\u6b4c\u5287\u9662.jpg|[[National Taichung Theater]], Taichung (2014)\nFile:Kaohsiung_Taiwan_Kaohsiung-Exhibition-Center-03.jpg|[[Kaohsiung Exhibition Center]], Kaohsiung (2014)\n\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Taiwan}}\n*[[List of tallest buildings in Taiwan]]\n*[[List of cities with most skyscrapers]]\n*[[Lingnan architecture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Asia in topic|Architecture of}}\n{{Taiwan topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Architecture Of Taiwan}}\n[[Category:Architecture of Taiwan| ]]\n", "text_old": "The '''architecture of Taiwan''' can be traced back to [[stilt house|stilt housing]] of the aborigines in [[prehistory|prehistoric times]]; to the building of fortresses and churches in the north and south used to colonize and convert the inhabitants during the [[Dutch Taiwan|Dutch]] and [[Spanish Taiwan|Spanish]] period; the [[Kingdom of Tungning|Tungning]] period when Taiwan was a base of [[anti-Qing sentiment]] and Minnan-style architecture was introduced; in [[Qing dynasty]] period, a mix of Chinese and Western architecture appeared and [[artillery battery]] flourished during Qing's [[Self-Strengthening Movement]]; During the [[Japanese rule of Taiwan]], the Minnan, [[Japanese culture|Japanese]] and [[Western culture|Western]] culture were main influencers in architectural designs and saw the introduction and use of [[reinforced concrete]]. Due to excessive Westernization as a colony, after the [[Retrocession Day|retrocession of Taiwan]] to the [[Republic of China (1912\u201349)|Republic of China]] in 1945 from Japan at the end of World War II, Chinese classical style became popular and entered into international mainstream as a postmodern design style. Today, Taiwanese architecture has undergone much diversification, every style of architecture can be seen.<ref>[http://www.dm.ncyu.edu.tw/history/history.htm {{in lang|zh}} History of Taiwanese architecture]</ref>\n\n== Prehistory (-1621) ==\n{{Main|Prehistory of Taiwan}}\nThe architecture of prehistoric Taiwan saw structures ranging from [[cave|cave dwellings]], [[stilt house|stilt housing]], to [[stone masonry]]. Primarily of [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]] architecture.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www2.wunan.com.tw/download/preview/1wb5.pdf |title=Pre-historic Taiwanese architecture, National Chiayi University - Dead link |language=zh |access-date=2017-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130509052820/http://www2.wunan.com.tw/download/preview/1wb5.pdf |archive-date=2013-05-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Taioldhouse.jpg|An observational painting of a stilt house of one of the [[Pingpu peoples|plains tribes]] as depicted in [[Liu Shi Qi\u2019s Taiwan Panorama Prints]] (\u516d\u5341\u4e03\u5169\u91c7\u98a8\u5716\u5408\u5377).\nFile:Mokka and their house.jpg|A stilt house of the [[Truku people|Truku tribe]].\nFile:Lanyu Ivalino Ia-gin village hill view.jpg|Modern and traditional houses coexisting in present day [[Tao people|Tao tribe]] settlement on [[Orchid Island]].\n</gallery>\n\n===Cave Dwelling===\nPrehistoric man made use of caves for their dwellings and Taiwan's oldest known civilization is the [[Changbin culture]] (\u9577\u6ff1\u6587\u5316) dating back to over 50,000 years. An example of an [[archaeological site]] of a cave dwelling is the [[Bashian Caves]] in [[Changbin, Taitung|Changbin Township]], [[Taitung County]] which is dated from between 5,500 and 30,000 years. The actual cave itself has a height of around ten [[metre|meters]] and can accommodate some ten persons.\n\n===Stilt Housing===\n{{Main|Stilt house}}\nSpread over the vast prehistoric [[Pacific Ocean]] and [[Indian Ocean]] areas, stilt houses vary greatly. In more recent times, Taiwanese aborigines make use of them for holding church meetings, as places to cool down and to hold ancestral activities. Apart from their cooling effect, stilt houses also have various functions such as avoiding [[miasma theory|miasma]], dampness, flood, and insects and snakes from entering, it is also easier to construct.\n\n===Stone Slab Housing===\n[[File:Paiwan.jpg|right|thumb|Stone slab house of the [[Paiwan people|Paiwan tribe]] taken by Japanese anthropologist [[Ushinosuke Mori]] prior to 1945.]]\n\nThe [[Paiwan people|Paiwan]] and [[Bunun people|Bunun]] tribes made houses using thatched roofing and made walls from stones, homes of nobles were decorated with elaborate wood carvings. The special characteristics of such houses is that dark colored building materials help conceal the buildings in its environment and the layered use of rocks mimic the scales of the [[Deinagkistrodon|hundred pacer snake]] that they worship.<ref>[http://www.e-tribe.org.tw/kungdavane/DesktopDefault.aspx?tabId=100 {{in lang|zh}} Kungdavane - Dead link]</ref>\n\n===Aboriginal Architecture===\n{{Main|Taiwanese aborigines}}\nChinese and aborigines made use of natural materials for basic construction materials such as straw, wood, bamboo, grass, stone, soil, etc. The types and styles vary depending on the environment, climate, and cultural influences of each tribe. For example, the [[Amis people|Amis]] tribe tend to live in larger communities and planned the layout of their community such as placement of communal homes and a plaza for matters of governance inside, planting a bamboo forest around the outside with camps and guard stations to defend against foreign aggressors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dmtip.gov.tw/Aborigines/Article.aspx?CategoryID=3&ClassID=10&TypeID=24&SubTypeID=0&RaceID=1 |title=Building structures of the Amis tribe, Digital Museum of Taiwan Indigenous Peoples |language=zh |access-date=2017-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425121410/http://www.dmtip.gov.tw/Aborigines/Article.aspx?CategoryID=3&ClassID=10&TypeID=24&SubTypeID=0&RaceID=1 |archive-date=2017-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The [[Atayal people|Atayal]] and [[Saisiyat people|Saisiyat]] tribes made their homes out of wood and bamboo while the [[Tao people|Tao]] tribe who live further away on [[Orchid Island]] and faced strong changes in seasonal weather such as typhoons, developed houses that made use of digging vertically into the ground to strengthen their foundations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dmtip.gov.tw/Aborigines/Article.aspx?CategoryID=3&ClassID=10&TypeID=24&SubTypeID=2&RaceID=12 |title=Housing layout of the Yami (Tao) tribe, Digital Museum of Taiwan Indigenous Peoples |language=zh |access-date=2017-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425122405/http://www.dmtip.gov.tw/Aborigines/Article.aspx?CategoryID=3&ClassID=10&TypeID=24&SubTypeID=2&RaceID=12 |archive-date=2017-04-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Dutch and Spanish settlement (1624\u20131662)==\n{{Main|Castle|Fortress}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Zeelandia model.JPG|[[Fort Zeelandia (Taiwan)|Fort Zeelandia]] was built by the Dutch in 1624 and is now known as Anping Fort.\nFile:Chihkan Tower 03.JPG|[[Fort Provintia]] was a bastion structure, the remains of which are now known as Chihkan Tower.\nFile:Atlas Blaeu-Van der Hem - Taioan.jpg|[[Anping District|Taioan Street]] (\u5927\u54e1\u5e02\u8857) was built by the Dutch and is now the present day Yanping Street (\u5ef6\u5e73\u8857) in Anping District, Tainan.\nFile:Official consulate fort santo domingo.jpg|[[Fort San Domingo]] was built by the Spanish in 1628 and after their defeat was rebuilt by the Dutch. It is known as \u00c2ng-mn\u0302g-si\u00e2\u207f (Red-haired Fort) after the Dutch people.\n</gallery>\n\nThe 16th century was a time of Western naval navigation, exploration and trade and also the shifting of power from the [[Ming dynasty]] to the [[Qing dynasty]]. Most of the architecture in Taiwan from this period were dominated by fortresses, primarily the Dutch [[Fengguiwei Fort]], [[Fort Zeelandia (Taiwan)|Fort Zeelandia]], [[Fort Provintia]] in the south and the Spanish [[Fort San Domingo]] to the north. The Dutch used red bricks in construction while the Spanish used stone. Both sides made use of ports and constructed fortresses to consolidate their power on the island. The fortresses were square shaped with an additional side for the installment of [[artillery]]. This period saw Taiwan architecture enter the peak of [[western culture|Western colonization]]. Such structures from this period represent the first generation of architectural works and is now listed as a world heritage by the Republic of China government.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dm.ncyu.edu.tw/vr/vr02_map/001/001-02.htm |title=Origins of Tamsui's Fort Zeelandia |access-date=2017-04-25 |language=zh |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804161209/http://www.dm.ncyu.edu.tw/vr/vr02_map/001/001-02.htm |archive-date=2012-08-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Kingdom of Tungning (1662\u20131682) == \n<gallery>\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u958b\u57fa\u5929\u540e\u5bae.JPG|Kaichi Matsu Temple (\u958b\u57fa\u5929\u540e\u5bae) in Tainan is one of the earliest temples dedicated to [[Mazu (goddess)|Mazu]].\nFile:PICT0342.JPG|[[Grand Matsu Temple]] used to be the palace of [[Zhu Shugui|Prince Ningjing]] of [[Southern Ming]] dynasty.\nFile:\u53f0\u5357\u5e02\u4e94\u5983\u5edf.jpg|[[Temple of the Five Concubines]] (1683), extended in 1746.\nFile:Temple of Confucius.jpg|[[Taiwan Confucian Temple]], Tainan (1665)\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u958b\u5143\u5bfa\u5c71\u9580.JPG|Kaiyuan Temple (\u958b\u5143\u5bfa), Tainan (1680)\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u6cd5\u83ef\u5bfa.JPG|Fahua Temple (\u6cd5\u83ef\u5bfa) was the former residence known as the Dream Butterfly Garden (\u5922\u8776\u5712 Mengdieyuan) of Li Maochun (\u674e\u8302\u6625)\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u5317\u6975\u6bbf.JPG|Arctic Palace (\u5317\u6975\u6bbf), Tainan (1661)\n</gallery>\n\n== Qing Dynasty (1683\u20131895) ==\n;Minnan architecture\n<gallery>\nFile:Old Governor-General of Taiwan.JPG|Fujian Taiwan Administrative Commissioner Yamen (\u798f\u5efa\u81fa\u7063\u627f\u5ba3\u5e03\u653f\u4f7f\u53f8\u8859\u9580)\nFile:Local Security Garrison of Qing Dynasty Taiwan Provincial Administration Hall, 2013.JPG|[[\u6b3d\u5dee\u884c\u81fa]]\nFile:\u53f0\u5317\u5e9c\u57ce\u5317\u9580.JPG|North Gate (\u627f\u6069\u9580 Cheng'enmen) of the [[Walls of Taipeh]]\nFile:\u53f0\u5317\u897f\u9580.jpg|West Gate (\u5bf6\u6210\u9580 Baochengmen) of the [[Walls of Taipeh]]\nFile:Taiwan Hsinchu YinXi Gate.JPG|Yensi Gate (\u8fce\u66e6\u9580), Hsinchu\nFile:Taiwan Castle North gate.JPG|North Gate of Taiwan Castle (\u53f0\u7063\u57ce), present day Watching Moon Pavilion (\u671b\u6708\u4ead) in [[Taichung Park]]\nFile:\u81fa\u7063\u5e9c\u57ce\u5927\u5357\u9580.jpg|Great South Gate of Tainan Prefecture\nFile:\u53f0\u5357\u5e02\u5927\u6771\u9580.JPG|Great East East of Tainan Prefecture\nFile:\u65e5\u6cbb\u6642\u671f\u958b\u5c71\u795e\u793e\u5165\u53e3.JPG|Koxinga Shrine, Tainan\nFile:FengshanEgate.jpg|East Gate of New Town (\u9cf3\u5c71\u7e23\u65b0\u57ce), in Fengshan County.\nFile:\u9727\u5cf0\u6797\u5bb6\u666f\u85b0\u6a13.jpg|Tower of Prospective Fragrance, [[Wufeng Lin Family Mansion and Garden]], Taichung (1864)\nFile:Court of Ding-Jing Hall, Lin Garden.JPG|Bridge in [[Lin Family Mansion and Garden]]\nFile:\u9e7f\u6e2f\u9f8d\u5c71\u5bfa\u5c71\u9580.jpg|[[Longshan Temple (Lukang)|Lukang Longshan Temple]], Changhua\nFile:Li teng-fang Historical Home ,TAIWAN.jpg|[[Lee Teng-fan's Ancient Residence]], Taoyuan\nFile:Lin AnTai Old HomeStead.jpg|[[Lin An Tai Historical House and Museum]], Taipei\nFile:Plain Aborigines Taipei.jpg|Houses constructed of mud and straw by the Siniticized [[Ketagalan people|Ketagalan tribe]] of Kanatsui settlement (\u572d\u6b66\u5352\u793e)\n</gallery>\n\n;\u5169\u5ee3\u3001\u6f6e\u6c55\u5efa\u7bc9\n<gallery>\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u5169\u5ee3\u6703\u9928\u53ca\u91cd\u9053\u5d07\u6587\u574a.jpg|Liangguanghui Hall (\u5169\u5ee3\u6703\u9928), Tainan\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u4e09\u5c71\u570b\u738b\u5edf (\u9ad8\u8655\u62cd\u651d).JPG|Three Mountain Kings Temple (\u4e09\u5c71\u570b\u738b\u5edf), Tainan\n</gallery>\n;Hakka architecture\n<gallery>\nFile:\u65b0\u5c4b\u8303\u59dc\u7956\u5802.jpg|New Fanjiang Ancestral Hall (\u65b0\u5c4b\u8303\u59dc\u7956\u5802), Taoyuan\nFile:\u65e5\u6cbb\u6642\u671f\u7684\u516d\u5806\u5fe0\u7fa9\u7960.JPG|Liudui Martyr's Shrine (\u516d\u5806\u5fe0\u7fa9\u7960), Pingtung\nFile:Peipu-temple.jpg|[[Beipu Citian Temple]], Hsinchu\nFile:Hukou Sanyuan Temple 20100731.jpg|Hukou Sanyuan Temple (\u6e56\u53e3\u4e09\u5143\u5bae), Hsinchu\nFile:\u58fd\u5c71\u5dd6\u89c0\u97f3\u5bfa.JPG|Shoushanyan Guanyin Temple (\u58fd\u5c71\u5dd6\u89c0\u97f3\u5bfa), Taoyuan\nFile:CKF2008030601.JPG|Beipu Tianshui Temple (\u5317\u57d4\u5929\u6c34\u5802), Hsinchu\nFile:Meinong East Gate Tower front view 20150124.jpg|[[Meinong East Gate Tower]], Kaohsiung\n</gallery>\n\n;Western-style architecture\n<gallery>\nFile:Immaculate Conception Cathedral of Taipei 001 in 1889.jpg|[[Immaculate Conception Cathedral, Taipei|Immaculate Conception Cathedral]], Taipei (1889)\nFile:\u524d\u91d1\u5929\u4e3b\u5802.jpg|[[Holy Rosary Cathedral, Kaohsiung|Holy Rosary Cathedral]], Kaohsiung (1861)\nFile:Oxford College, Aletheia University 20050702.jpg|[[Aletheia University|Oxford College]], Tamsui (1882)\nFile:Tamsui customs officers residence.jpg|[[Tamsui Customs Officers' Residence]], Tamsui (1870)\nFile:\u81fa\u5357\u6771\u8208\u6d0b\u884c.JPG|Julius Mannich & CO., Tainan\n</gallery>\n\n== Period of Japanese rule (1896\u20131945) ==\n;Western-style Architecture\n<gallery>\nFile:Taichung Park-1.JPG|Nanyang-style Mid-Lake Pavilion (\u6e56\u5fc3\u4ead) in [[Taichung Park]], Taichung (1908)\nFile:\u570b\u5b9a\u53e4\u8e5f\u81fa\u5357\u5730\u65b9\u6cd5\u9662.jpg|Tainan District Court (1912)\nFile:\u53f0\u9435\u65b0\u7af9\u8eca\u7ad9(2).jpg|[[Hsinchu railway station|Hsinchu Station]] (1913)\nFile:\u81f